 different works, but their early lives and writings display provocative kinships, while also indicating the divergent paths the two authors would take en route to literary greatness. The ten new critical essays here, written by leading specialists in nineteenth-century, Russian literature, give fresh, sophisticated readings to works from the first decade of the literary life of each Russian author-for Dostoevsky, the 1840s; for Tolstoy, the 1850s. Collectively, these essays yield composite portraits of these two artists as young men finding their literary way. At the same time, they show how the early works merit appreciation for themselves, before their authors were Titans.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aRussian literaturey19th centuryxCriticism and interpretation. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aAllen, Elizabeth Cheresh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllen, Elizabeth Cheresh, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBagby, Lewis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmerson, Caryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEmerson, Caryl.1 aFusso, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnapp, Liza, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLounsbery, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Robin Feuer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 